    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2866360898" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2866360898" />
    <a title="D. Jeter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/98830948-d-jeter"><img alt="D. Jeter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561123322p2/98830948.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2866360898?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D. Jeter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="D. Jeter" href="/user/show/98830948-d-jeter">D. Jeter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2866360898" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3584096568007381521">Grayson Wolf was once the greatest assassin in the world (nicknamed Mors), but he is now an old man. He simply exists day-to-day as he waits for the Grim Reaper to one day come and take his soul. However, that all changes when he suddenly finds himself protecting a young girl from the dark forces and evil men pursuing her. <br/><br/>This is a tale of atonement. After a lifetime of killing, Grayson has the chance to do one thing right. He tries to fight it, but at the end of the day he has a good soul and </span>
  <span id="freeText3584096568007381521" style="display:none">Grayson Wolf was once the greatest assassin in the world (nicknamed Mors), but he is now an old man. He simply exists day-to-day as he waits for the Grim Reaper to one day come and take his soul. However, that all changes when he suddenly finds himself protecting a young girl from the dark forces and evil men pursuing her. <br /><br />This is a tale of atonement. After a lifetime of killing, Grayson has the chance to do one thing right. He tries to fight it, but at the end of the day he has a good soul and can't turn away from a person in need. The novel is written from the 1st person POV. Therefore, it gives us a great insight into Grayson's perspective. His voice has that "old-person dryness" to it, and the entire tone of the novel encompasses a bit of the western flair. Grayson is a soldier, not a story-teller, and it shows in the way the novel is written. He is basically a tank in many of the action scenes, bulldozing through his foes. I see his size as symbolic for the unstoppable force that is Mors. <br /><br />There is very little sleek style to this novel, but there is a lot of substance. Grayson's story is powerful, and I love how the novel spends very little time with other characters besides him. It gives the reader a great ability to bond with Grayson, and truly get to know him and his psyche. He has this rawness to him that defines his character and attitude. That is honestly the best part of the story. <br /><br />Through Grayson is such a "fantastical" character, there is a realness to him that connects with the reader. He is humanized from this legendary figure into an old man who is filled with regret and looking for that second chance, even though he does not realize it sometimes. <br /><br />The fight scenes, which have been commented on already, are very well done and brutal. There is no sensationalizing of violence in this novel. Instead, it's gritty and raw. It's a consequential means to an end. One of the main themes in this novel is the ramifications of a violent life. <br /><br />The ending is perfect. The way Habib ties everything together is a great wrap-up to a powerful story. I think anyone who reads this will be inspired by Grayon's journey of atonement. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3584096568007381521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


