    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2827671579" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2827671579" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90154915-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586450931p2/90154915.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2827671579?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/90154915-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2827671579" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer728967645910237099"><b> Redemption Story at its Finest! </b><br/><br/>This novel is a definite 5 star rating from me. It&apos;s unlike any other work of Ammar Habib&apos;s that I&apos;ve ever read. However, it still possesses that same dramatic grandeur that I love about all his works. This book is a redemption story that follows an older protagonist, giving it a unique spin since most of Ammar&apos;s works usually follow younger protagonists. <br/><br/>Starting with the character of Grayson Wolf, he is the perfect hero for this sort of story. Being an ex-assas</span>
  <span id="freeText728967645910237099" style="display:none"><b> Redemption Story at its Finest! </b><br /><br />This novel is a definite 5 star rating from me. It's unlike any other work of Ammar Habib's that I've ever read. However, it still possesses that same dramatic grandeur that I love about all his works. This book is a redemption story that follows an older protagonist, giving it a unique spin since most of Ammar's works usually follow younger protagonists. <br /><br />Starting with the character of Grayson Wolf, he is the perfect hero for this sort of story. Being an ex-assassin, he comes into this story with a lot of baggage. All his sins have caught up to him, and he has been in hiding for the past few decades. He is a shadow of the man he was before. He is constantly haunted by demons and the visions of a woman named Ophelia. Grayson begs for death. The irony is that it seems that he can't die. Death alludes him because life itself has become his punishment. All this creates a very relatable, three-dimensional character. <br /><br />The inciting action of this story is when Grayson's old comrade shows up and needs help protecting a girl from the forces pursuing them. Grayson is reluctant, but he is forced into the situation. What follows is a quasi-western style pursuit where Grayson and the girl (Anna) must stay one step ahead of their pursuers. <br /><br />Just as you'd expect for this gritty and dark redemption story, there is a lot of action and a lot of violence. It's very bloody and detailed, and there's no glamour to it. It reminds me of the fight scenes from the Punisher TV series or John Wick/Logan. It's very brutal, but it is for a good reason. This book is about the ramifications of violence, as other reviewers have stated. <br /><br />Through the course of being on the run with Anna, Grayson begins to grow attached to the girl and see himself in her. This is when his walls start to come down and we finally see this legendary assassin and warrior as human. The heart of this story lies in the private scenes between Grayson and Anna or Grayson and just himself. <br /><br />There is a lot of symbolism peppered in throughout the story. Grayson Wolf's name is symbolic in and of itself and the symbols of grey wolves and wolves in general is a main one. A lot of the symbols and metaphors make sense as you read the book, so I won't spoil them. <br /><br />I read this entire book within 2 days, which is not something common for me. At its heart, the story is a character-driven tale about a lost man finding purpose again. He has spent a lifetime in the darkness, a lifetime of bloodshed and death. However, he finally gets a chance to do something right. He can save Anna from the darkness, save her from the abyss that trapped him in his childhood and has destroyed his life. This chance at redemption is the core of THE LEGENDARY WOLF's plot. And I absolutely love this angle! <br /><br />I'd recommend this novel to any fans of thrillers! </span>
  <a data-text-id="728967645910237099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

