<div id="review_2811315977" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2811315977" />
    <a title="Aaron" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/80064765-aaron"><img alt="Aaron" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1529001571p2/80064765.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2811315977?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aaron" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aaron" href="/user/show/80064765-aaron">Aaron</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2811315977" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9854044962543013864"><b> An Excellent Story of Redemption </b><br/><br/>Thank you to the author for the ARC of this terrific book! <br/><br/>This is another great work by Ammar Habib, one that is very different from his previous ones. <b> <i> The Legendary Wolf </i></b>  is a brutal tale of redemption. The story opens up with Grayson Wolf, the protagonist, being in a very dark place. He was once the greatest agent and assassin in the world, and he had earned the nickname of Mors (named after the Roman embodiment of death). But that was a long time ago... a</span>
  <span id="freeText9854044962543013864" style="display:none"><b> An Excellent Story of Redemption </b><br /><br />Thank you to the author for the ARC of this terrific book! <br /><br />This is another great work by Ammar Habib, one that is very different from his previous ones. <b> <i> The Legendary Wolf </i></b>  is a brutal tale of redemption. The story opens up with Grayson Wolf, the protagonist, being in a very dark place. He was once the greatest agent and assassin in the world, and he had earned the nickname of Mors (named after the Roman embodiment of death). But that was a long time ago... and he is an old man now. <br /><br />Grayson is a broken man and spends his days drinking his life away, thinking that his best years are behind him. As the book says, he is a warrior who has "lived past his expiration date." He is now haunted by his demons, demons that are a ramification for the life of violence he once lived. The main demon is one named Ophelia, and she constantly reminds him of one unspeakable act he committed that ultimately destroyed his life decades ago and made him go into hiding. <br /><br />Everything changes when a former comrade shows up and pulls Grayson back into the dark world of espionage and death. This comrade is trying to protect something, and he needs Grayon's help. Now hunted by men, ones that are not too different that what he once was, Grayson must again unleash the beast inside him to survive. He must forgo being Grayson Wolf. He must make his final hurrah and again be the Legendary Wolf!<br /><br />This is a great story. Even with all the great action sequences, the greatest struggle in this story is Grayon's internal battle. He must find a meaning to his life again. There is a TON of symbolism in Grayson's character, and I couldn't help but compare him to famous warriors for ancient literature, such as Samson and Achilles. Just like those legends, Grayson too was invincible in the eyes of his opponents. And also just like those legends, Grayson's demise came from one weakness he had. <br /><br />I found Grayson's character as being symbolic for old age. Many people lose their friends as they grow older and become isolated. This is exactly where Grayson is at in the beginning of the novel. He has lost his way and has no purpose. Finding his purpose is a theme that is at the crux of this story. <br /><br />From the characters to the pacing to the tone, there is just so much to love here. The novel is written from the 1st person POV, and reading it through Grayson's eyes gives the reader a great perspective into his character. The gritty tone and voice give this a western flair, reminding me of the old westerns I grew up watching. <br /><br />Habib writes this with an expert flair that pulls the reader into the story. This is a textbook page-turner, and I'd recommend it to any reader who enjoys the action/thriller genre, especially ones that are character-driven. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9854044962543013864" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


